 Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the medieval vernacular form of the Latin name   Laetitia .  It was in use in Britain in the Middle Ages, but then fell out of use until revived by the Victorians. It is now once again out of fashion."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Isabelle","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabel","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Attainment’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Létice Isabelle l'Archevêque de Parthenay was born about 1276, in Parthenay, Deux-Sèvres, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France, her father, Guillaume VI de PARTHENAY, was 27 and her mother, Jeanne de MONFORT, was 28. She had at least 2 daughters with Maurice IV de Belleville-Montaigu."},"et":{"ABT 1276–":"umbes 1276–Surnud","1276–Female":"1276–Surnud","1270–1358":"1270–1358","1286–1359":"1286–1359","1260–1303":"1260–1303","1300–1359":"1300–1359","1251–1315":"1251–1315","1250–1291":"1250–1291","1286":"1286","15 janvier 1300":"15. jaanuar 1300","1251":"1251","1250":"1250","1260":"1260","1270":"1270","1291":"1291","1315":"1315","1359":"1359","1303":"1303","1358":"1358","ABT 1276":"umbes 1276","1300":"1300",